  "source_test": "HEC.FDA.ModelTest/unittests/AlternativeTest.cs (ComputeEEAD_Test, SingleBaseScenario_EqadMatchesInputAndExcludesLifeLoss, SingleFutureScenario_EqadMatchesInputAndExcludesLifeLoss, LifeLossResultsExcludedFromEqad)",
  "note": "Phase 6 Task 9. Two case `kind`s, both dispatched by run_alternative/EvalAlternative: `compute_eqad` (method `compute_eqad`, args [baseYearEAD, baseYear, mostLikelyFutureEAD, mostLikelyFutureYear, periodOfAnalysis, discountRate]) calls Alternative::compute_eqad directly -- no ScenarioResults involved, THE tightest oracle pin (interpolate/present-value/PVIFA), transcribed from AlternativeTest.ComputeEEAD_Test's 8 [InlineData] rows verbatim (abs tol 0.005, matching the C# test's own `Assert.Equal(expected, actual, .01)` looser 2-decimal literal -- PIN captures the full-precision value). `annualization` cases build a base/future ScenarioResults directly from AggregatedConsequencesBinned constructed from an already-built DynamicHistogram (the (string,string,unique_ptr<DynamicHistogram>,int,ConsequenceType,RiskType) ctor, Task 9 un-severance), matching AlternativeTest's own `new DynamicHistogram(Enumerable.Range(start,count)...)` + `new AggregatedConsequencesBinned(...)` construction exactly -- `values_start`/`values_count` reproduce `Enumerable.Range(start, count).Select(i => (double)i)`. Every consequence entry uses RiskType.Fail (the real default AggregatedConsequencesBinned/StudyAreaConsequencesBinned::GetConsequenceResult search against, NOT the RiskType.Total convention scenario_results.json/alternative_results.json's OWN impact-area builder uses for THEIR different testing purpose) so process_base_and_future_year_scenario_results' 4-arg GetConsequenceResult lookups (which default riskType to Fail) actually find their matches. `annualization_single_base`/`annualization_single_future` supply only one side (`future_impact_area`/`base_impact_area` is null) -- exercises the single-scenario null-coalesce + identical-scenario short-circuit (no discounting), each impact area holding both a Damage and a LifeLoss consequence result (mirrors SingleBaseScenario_EqadMatchesInputAndExcludesLifeLoss/SingleFutureScenario_...): `sample_mean_eqad` is PIN (delegates to base_year_scenario_results_.SampleMeanExpectedAnnualConsequences, which equals the input histogram's own SampleMean exactly -- the identical branch never recomputes it), `eqad_count_by_type` is a structural (hand-derivable, not PIN) count of EqadResults.ConsequenceResultList entries matching a ConsequenceType: Damage=1 (survives ScenarioResults::convert_to_study_area_consequences_by_quantile's ConsequenceType::Damage filter), LifeLoss=0 (filtered out -- 'there is no concept of EqAD for life loss'). `annualization_lifeloss_excluded` supplies BOTH sides as two DISTINCT ScenarioResults with the SAME impact_area_id and matching (damage_category, asset_category) Damage categories but different histogram values (so ScenarioResults::equals is false -- takes process_base_and_future_year_scenario_results, exercising the real 25000-step iterate_on_eqad Monte-Carlo-quantile walk end to end, not just the identical-scenario short-circuit) plus a LifeLoss category on BOTH sides (mirrors LifeLossResultsExcludedFromEqad) -- `sample_mean_eqad` is PIN (the real discounted quantile-walk mean), `eqad_count_by_type` Damage=1/LifeLoss=0 (structural, same rationale as above), and `base_has_lifeloss`/`future_has_lifeloss` are structural (exact 1.0) checks that alt.base_year_scenario_results()/future_year_scenario_results() still carry the LifeLoss data post-compute (both sides are genuinely distinct objects here, so the port's single-scenario-aliasing ownership deviation -- see alternative.hpp's class comment -- does not apply and both fields are faithfully populated, unlike the single-scenario cases above where only base_year_scenario_results_ is ever populated by design). `expected: \"PIN\"` gate-captured, never hand-derived; the 8 ComputeEqad literals below are a cross-check against the C# unit test's own rounded InlineData, not the fixture's actual pinned value.",
